Uses of Class
ca.uqac.lif.cep.Processor

  • Packages that use Processor 
    Package Description
    ca.uqac.lif.cep
    Elementary classes defining all the basic concepts of event stream processing.
    ca.uqac.lif.cep.cli
    Rudimentary interactive command-line interpreter and GUI.
    ca.uqac.lif.cep.concurrency  
    ca.uqac.lif.cep.functions
    Definition of the Function object and basic concepts around functions.
    ca.uqac.lif.cep.input
    Processors to handle conversions to and from various data formats.
    ca.uqac.lif.cep.interpreter
    Interpreter for queries written in ESQL, the Event Stream Query Language.
    ca.uqac.lif.cep.io
    Processors to handle input and output of data from external sources, such as files and pipes.
    ca.uqac.lif.cep.tmf
    Processors to manipulate traces of generic events.

      Subclasses of Processor in ca.uqac.lif.cep.tmf 
      Modifier and Type Class and Description
      class  Collator
      Takes the output of multiple processors, and puts them into a named map.
      class  CountDecimate
      Returns one input event and discards the next n-1.
      class  Demultiplexer
      Converts a sequence of n consecutive events into an event that is a vector of size n.
      class  Dropper
      Takes a set of elements as input, and returns as many output events as there are elements in that set.
      class  Filter
      Discards events from an input trace based on a selection criterion.
      class  Fork
      Duplicates an input trace into two or more output traces.
      class  Freeze
      Repeatedly outputs the first event it has received.
      class  Insert
      Inserts an event a certain number of times before letting the input events through.
      class  Last
      Processor that only returns the last element of its input trace.
      class  Multiplexer
      Merges the contents of multiple traces into a single trace.
      class  NaryToArray
      Converts n input traces into a single output trace, whose events are arrays of n elements
      class  Passthrough
      Returns its input as its output.
      class  Prefix
      Returns the first n input events and discards the following ones.
      class  QueueSink
      Sink that accumulates events into queues.
      class  QueueSource
      Source whose input is a queue of objects.
      class  QueueSourceBatch
      Operates like QueueSource, except that it dumps all its queue at once, instead of releasing the events one by one.
      class  Sink
      Receives input events and stores them.
      class  SinkLast
      Sink that remembers only the last event sent to it.
      class  Slicer
      Separates an input trace into different "slices".
      class  SmartFork
      Duplicates an input event into two or more output traces.
      class  Source
      Produces output events from no input.
      class  Splicer
      Joins multiple traces as a single one.
      class  StateSlicer
      Separates an input trace into different "slices".
      class  TimeDecimate
      After returning an input event, discards all others for the next n seconds.
      class  Trim
      Discards the first n events of the input, and outputs the remaining ones.
      class  Window
      Simulates the application of a "sliding window" to a trace.
      class  WindowFunction
      Takes a sliding window of n successive input events, passes them to an n-ary function and outputs the result.
